b'' b'organization: compact solutions, canberra act australia' b'' b' this may be a very naive question but is there any' b' basis for the' b' claim that a cpu will get hotter when a' b' computationally intensive' b' job is running? my friend claims that there will be' b' little difference' b' in the temperature of an idle cpu and a cpu running a' b' computationally' b' intensive job.' b'' b"from what i've seen in coursework, most cpus never actually" b'"idle". they will continue to service interrupts, etc.,' b'etc. the clock will always be running at n mhz no matter' b"what it's doing." b'' b'i suppose depending on the instruction, the cpu may use' b'circuitry which has more transistors than other' b'instructions, but if you consider the additional heat' b'generated by only a handful of additional, tiny resistors' b"and then spread that heat dissipation over the cpu's" b'packaging, the change in temperature to the immediate' b'environment (ie. the surface of the package) will be' b'negligible.' b'' b'cheers, ben' b'------------------------------------------------------------------------------' b'ben j. elliston' b'bachelor of engineering (computer engineering) b'___ooo_( )_ooo__' b'uucp: ..!uunet!munnari!sserve.adfa.oz.au!compsol!root' b'fidonet: b'------------------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'* origin: compact solutions canberra act australia 